This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring April 15, 2015, as a Day of Remembrance for President Abraham Lincoln. The proclamation highlights Lincoln's belief in a united nation and his dedication to preserving liberty. It emphasizes his leadership during the Civil War and his efforts to reunite the country. The proclamation calls upon all Americans to honor Lincoln's life and legacy through appropriate programs and activities. It also directs the flag to be flown at half-staff on that day and encourages individuals to do the same.